\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
USB key / USB drive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the simplest way to share documents.
 Simply copy your work directory to an USB key, tell Paperwork to use it,
 and you're done.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beware: You should backup your USB key from time to time on another one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
File Synchronization applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Those applications synchronize a local directory with a remote server (or
 cloud).
 All the changes you do in your folder are applied on the server.
 All the changes applied on the servers are applied to the computers that
 connect to it.
 The server can belong to you or to someone else (usually a company).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beware: If you choose to host your documents on someone else server (DropBox,
 OneDrive, etc), they can access all your documents.
 Paperwork does not cipher them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Paperwork is tested daily with SparkleShare.
 While this is not the easiest one to use, Sparkleshare let you host your
 files yourself.
 Using DropBox or OneDrive can make sense if you're sharing not-so-confidential
 documents with others (associations, etc).
\end_layout

